body:
I've fixed this here

https://beta.rclone.org/v1.39-002-gef89f1f1/ (uploaded in 15-30 mins)

I can't change the time format as that will break the other webdav providers (eg nextcloud) so I've added in an alternative parsing format for mydrive.
Confirmed fix works in the beta. Thanks.
Thanks. Let me know if you have any more problems with my drive and I'll fix them!

```
```


I have downloaded the beta version as you can see. Thanks for helping !

OK, I found the problem!

The url of my nextcloud was not the right one. Maybe you should change your doc and specify that the webdav url is the one provided in the nextcloud doc : `https://example.com/nextcloud/remote.php/dav/files/USERNAME/` and not `https://example.com/nextcloud/remote.php/dav/`.

Seems to work like a charm now :-D

```
2018/01/16 10:22:56 Failed to ls: couldn't list files: parsing time "Wed May 17 15:31:58 UTC 2017" as "Mon, 02 Jan 2006 15:04:05 -0700": cannot parse " May 17 15:31:58 UTC 2017" as ", "

```


Hi @ncw,

Thanks for the reply.

This is a webdav hosted by the company I work for. They are reluctant (as most companys are) to change things. 

I tested with the following and it seems to be working

`timeFormatU = time.UnixDate `

Thanks

Great thanks.. I'll merge that now.  It will be in the next beta

issue.title: Listing with webdav not working with NextCloud external storages

repository.name: rclone
repository.description: "rsync for cloud storage" - Google Drive, S3, Dropbox, Backblaze B2, One Drive, Swift, Hubic, Wasabi, Google Cloud Storage, Azure Blob, Azure Files, Yandex Files

issue.body:
When listing a webdav (NextCloud) remote I get the following error

```
rclone ls myremote:
2018/07/27 23:44:13 ERROR : : error listing: couldn't list files: parsing time "" as "Mon Jan _2 15:04:05 MST 2006": cannot parse "" as "Mon"
2018/07/27 23:44:13 Failed to ls: couldn't list files: parsing time "" as "Mon Jan _2 15:04:05 MST 2006": cannot parse "" as "Mon"
```

I tried the current release v1.42 and also a build from the current revision 9c90b5e both on Windows 10 with amd64 architecture.
I found out the problem is that I have an external storage configured in NextCloud and the corresponding file entry has no modification time:

```
  <d:response>
    <d:href>/remote.php/webdav/ftp/</d:href>
    <d:propstat>
      <d:prop>
        <d:resourcetype>
          <d:collection/>
        </d:resourcetype>
        <d:quota-used-bytes>5</d:quota-used-bytes>
        <d:quota-available-bytes>-3</d:quota-available-bytes>
        <d:getetag>"5581aa796f9be"</d:getetag>
      </d:prop>
      <d:status>HTTP/1.1 200 OK</d:status>
    </d:propstat>
    <d:propstat>
      <d:prop>
        <d:getlastmodified/>
        <d:getcontentlength/>
        <d:getcontenttype/>
      </d:prop>
      <d:status>HTTP/1.1 404 Not Found</d:status>
    </d:propstat>
  </d:response>
```

This bug is somewhat related to #1952, however the problem here is not the wrong time format but the missing modification time.
I can confirm that it works with the following dirty hack in UnmarshalXML in webdav/api/types.go

```
if (v=="") {
	*t = Time(time.Now())
	return nil
}
```

However, I think the proper way of solving this might be evaluating the d:status tag and see if it is OK before parsing the properties.

body:
Just got the same problem with a pCloud directory.

root@HV-1:/localdir# rclone lsf pCloud:"pCloud Backup/x/y" -vv
2024/06/11 11:19:07 DEBUG : rclone: Version "v1.66.0" starting with parameters ["rclone" "lsf" "pCloud:pCloud Backup/x/y" "-vv"]
2024/06/11 11:19:07 DEBUG : Creating backend with remote "pCloud:pCloud Backup/x/y"
2024/06/11 11:19:07 DEBUG : Using config file from "/root/.config/rclone/rclone.conf"
2024/06/11 11:19:07 ERROR : : error listing: couldn't list files: parsing time "\"Sat, 06 Oct J632 05:39:02 +0000\"" as "\"Mon, 02 Jan 2006 15:04:05 -0700\"": cannot parse "J632 05:39:02 +0000\"" as "2006"
2024/06/11 11:19:07 DEBUG : 5 go routines active
2024/06/11 11:19:07 Failed to lsf with 2 errors: last error was: error in ListJSON: couldn't list files: parsing time "\"Sat, 06 Oct J632 05:39:02 +0000\"" as "\"Mon, 02 Jan 2006 15:04:05 -0700\"": cannot parse "J632 05:39:02 +0000\"" as "2006"

meanwhile got no problem with other directories.

@JC-LB This looks like a corruption in the pcloud data "Sat, 06 Oct J632 05:39:02 +0000" isn't a valid timestamp however you squint at it! If you can see this in the web interface I'd report it to pcloud support.
